THE SABC board has finally served acting group CEO, James Aguma, with a suspension letter.&nbsp;Aguma, who was allegedly on leave over the past few weeks received his suspension letter on Thursday.The DA yesterday welcomed the suspension, saying he was &ldquo;central and complicit&rdquo; to the dire straits the public broadcaster has been facing.The DA&rsquo;s Shadow Minister of Communications Phumzile van Damme yesterday said the party had been calling for his suspension for some time, following his approving &ldquo;lots of bad decisions and giving it financial backing&rdquo;.SABC spokesperson, Kaizer Kganyago, confirmed the suspension, but said he would not reveal any further details &ldquo;due to internal processes&rdquo;.Group Executive for Media, Technology and Infrastructure, Tseliso Ralitabo, has been appointed as the acting group CEO in the interim.The ANC Study Group on the Standing Committee on Public Accounts (Scopa) yesterday also welcomed Aguma&rsquo;s suspension. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re confident of the efforts by the Interim SABC Board in their commitment of restoring good governance and public confidence in our public broadcaster,&rdquo; Scopa chairperson Mnyamezeli Booi said in a statement.It was reported on Friday that Aguma faced suspension for providing an affidavit in Hlaudi Motsoeneng&rsquo;s misconduct case saying the board did not take a resolution to discipline Motsoeneng, &ldquo;yet he was in a board meeting when the decision was taken and in fact he supported the decision&rdquo;.Aguma reportedly gave Motsoeneng permission to hold what Van Damme referred to as his &ldquo;infamous press conference degrading the SABC&rdquo; on 19 April.